According to EIOPA, an undertaking's liquidity risk management policy should cover the following items [eiopa_guidelines_system_of_governance__0025__guideline-24-liquidity-risk-management-p]:
- The procedure for determining the level of mismatch between cash inflows and outflows, including expected cash flows of direct insurance and reinsurance such as claims, lapses, or surrenders [eiopa_guidelines_system_of_governance__0025__guideline-24-liquidity-risk-management-p];
- Consideration of total liquidity needs in the short and medium term, including an appropriate liquidity buffer to guard against a liquidity shortfall [eiopa_guidelines_system_of_governance__0025__guideline-24-liquidity-risk-management-p];
- Consideration of the level and monitoring of liquid assets, including a quantification of potential costs or financial losses arising from an enforced realisation [eiopa_guidelines_system_of_governance__0025__guideline-24-liquidity-risk-management-p];
- Identification and costs of alternative financing tools [eiopa_guidelines_system_of_governance__0025__guideline-24-liquidity-risk-management-p]; and
- Consideration of the effect on the liquidity situation of expected new business [eiopa_guidelines_system_of_governance__0025__guideline-24-liquidity-risk-management-p].
